 Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Cadwgon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Cadogan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cadogan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire and Glamorgan) and Irish (of Welsh origin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Catgucaun</i>, <i>Catguocawn</i>, modernized as <i>Cadwgon</i>. It is composed of <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. See also   Wogan  . The surname is stressed, like its Welsh original, on the penultimate syllable, hence its occasional development to   Duggan  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ceadagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceadagán</i>’."]}]},{"name":"Nest","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of <i>Nest</i>, a Welsh pet form of <b>Agnes</b> ; the name of the grandmother of the 12th-century chronicler Giraldus Cambrensis (‘Gerald the Welshman’)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nest verch Madog ap Cadwgon was born in 1165, her father, Madog II ap Cadwgan II of Nannau, was -35 and her mother, Efa verch Madog, was -45. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Einion ap Seisyllt. She died in Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1165–":"1165–Surnud","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1167–1250":"1167–1250","1218–1283":"1218–1283","1224–Male":"1224–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1216–Male":"1216–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1258–Female":"1258–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1165":"1165","1283":"1283","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","Abt 1260":"umbes 1260","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","1210":"1210","about 1258":"umbes 1258","1218":"1218","Meirionydd,,Merionethshire,Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Cyfeiliog, Montgomery, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Nannau Hall, Merionethshire, Wales":"Nannau Hall, Merionethshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1165–":"1165–Kuollut","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","1167–1250":"1167–1250","1218–1283":"1218–1283","1224–Male":"1224–Kuollut","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","1216–Male":"1216–Kuollut","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1258–Female":"1258–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1210–Fe